Date: Mon, 07 Apr 1997 18:26:19 -0500 (EST)
From: Claude D Betts <bettscd@battelle.org>
Subject: Re: PRO/EDR> Hepatitis A, strawberries - USA
Please excuse me if I am but sharing my limited knowledge on this matter. I
would like to know how hard is the evidence that incriminates the
strawberries coming from Mexico? From the little I have seen, the
epidemiological evidence seems quite weak and circumstantial. One has to
wonder if, in a political environment that is exploiting anti-immigrant
sentiments, blaming Mexico for a foodborne outbreak could be an easy way
out, given lack of hard data.
I haven't kept myself up to date on where we are with lab techniques in
Hepatitis A. Is it technically feasible to obtain evidence of viral
particles from suspect sources? If this were the case, positive viral
detection from incriminated Mexican frozen strawberries and negative from US
frozen strawberries would establish indubitable evidence of the alleged
contamination.
If this is not technically feasible, then we are left with calculating
attack rates in those who consume or not the suspect strawberries. However,
the long incubation period of Hepatitis A (+/- 4 weeks), makes it
particularly difficult to establish common source foodborne outbreaks,
unless they are extremely obvious.
Hepatitis A is an RNA enterovirus, that presents an epidemiological behavior
similar to that of polio (also an RNA enterovirus) before vaccines where
available. Improvements in sanitary conditions interrupted early fecal oral
transmission, to the point that large pools of susceptible children were
exposedto polio virus when they were no longer toddlers. The older a person,
the more likely to have clinical manifestations of disease when exposed to
polio. Polio infection among toddlers was usually asymptomatic. The same
happens with Hepatitis A infection.
Therefore, an outbreak in a school or a school district, may be the result
of a large concentration of susceptible individuals, where even minor breaks
in sanitary measures (for example, less hand washing among staff and
students in a school cafeteria) may make room for the introduction and rapid
dissemination of Hepatitis A virus. A situation like this can easily make
life impossible for epidemiologists, who are investigating such outbreaks.
Every one wants there to be a single culprit on which to put all the blame,
because once the culprit is found, heroic measures can be taken and everyone
can feel safe again...
>From my personal experience as a national epidemiologist in a Latin American
country, in more cases than not, it was impossible to establish the single
common source in most cases of Hepatitis A. An exception to the above, was
when hepatitis A outbreaks occurred in day care center staff and/or family
members of toddlers who were in day care centers. But that's another story...
Claude Betts
Medical Epidemiologist
