From: AlaskaRay@aol.com
Date: Thu, 10 Apr 1997 09:49:37 -0400 (EDT)
Subject: Re: PRO> Hepatitis A, strawberries
It's been very interesting hearing the news reports and reading the Promed
postings regarding the hepatitis A outbreak associated with Mexican grown
strawberries. Having spent several years in Mexico I was often cautioned
about eating any uncooked strawberries in Mexico, even if well washed.
Strawberries grow close to the ground and in many parts of Mexico,
irrigation is accomplished with aquas negras (black water or sewer water).
This easily contaminates ground hugging plants such as strawberries with
whatever pathogen may be present in the water. Because of the highly
irregular surface of the strawberries where bubbles and organic material can
adhere, washing and disinfecting is often inadequate. I was specifically
warned about the risk of aquiring cysticercosis from eating strawberries in
Mexico.
---
Raymond Weinstein, M.D.
Dale City, Va.
[I must declare a personal bias. I too, like Claude Betts, have had great
difficulty in understanding how only two nearby schools in northern USA
could come down with Hepatitis A infections and all the other schools and
establishments sharing the same shipment should be free of disease. By a
stretch of the imagination all the strawberries from a single contaminated
strawberry field, which can be large, in 1996 might end up at two near
adjoining establishments a year later in 1997, but it is hard. Logically, if
the Mexican irrigation water was to blame if only on a limited series of
farms, some other cases should have occurred elsewhere in other schools,
especially with the high attack rates reported in the two schools indicating
a significant risk and batch contamination. If the contamination was more
widespread, there is even more reason to not expect a very localised
expression. They cannot all have been prevented by serum innoculations. And
if 'aquas negras' are widely used as claimed, disease outbreaks should be a
regular occurence and would be associated with a range of field crops and
fruits.
Martin Hugh-Jones, ProMED Moderator.]
